              <fr:mainmatter>
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;i. &quot;">
        For every rank-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> prime ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {p}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_\mathfrak {p}]]></fr:tex> is normal (or, equivalently, regular);
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;ii. &quot;">
        For every rank-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\geq 2]]></fr:tex> prime ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {p}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, the depth of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_\mathfrak {p}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\geq 2]]></fr:tex>.
        (cf. EGA IV 5.8.6.)
      </html:li>

    </html:ol>
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>We assume this criterion here, but it should also appear in the section on flatness.
    Its main advantage is that it does not suppose a priori that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is reduced, nor a fortiori that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is integral.
    Here, we can already suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\dim  A=\dim  B\neq 0]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>By the statements at the start of this section, the rank-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> (resp. rank-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\geq 2]]></fr:tex>) prime ideals <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {p}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> are exactly the intersections of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> with the rank-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> (resp. rank-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\geq 2]]></fr:tex>) prime ideals <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {q}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.
    Finally, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {p}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {q}]]></fr:tex> correspond to one another, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B_\mathfrak {q}]]></fr:tex> is étale over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_\mathfrak {p}]]></fr:tex>, and thus of the same depth as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_\mathfrak {p}]]></fr:tex>, and is regular if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_\mathfrak {p}]]></fr:tex> is (by <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.9.1" href="sga1-i.9.1.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.9.1" />).
    Applying <fr:link type="local" href="sga1-i.9-serres-criterion.xml" addr="sga1-i.9-serres-criterion" title="SGA 1: Étale covers and the fundamental group › Étale morphisms › Invariance properties › First proof › Serre's criterion">Serre's criterion</fr:link>, we see that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is normal if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
